# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antioxidant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] This preparation allows for the use of waste chloro-organic compounds to form useful amines using inexpensive and readily available ammonia.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] The racemic mixture of this chiral compound may be separated into enantiomers by conversion into the diastereomeric tartaric acid ammonium salt.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] After purification of the diastereomer, the diamine can be regenerated by treatment of the ammonium salt with sodium hydroxide.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] Alternate reagents for chiral resolution include *N*-*p*-toluenesulfonylaspartic acid, *N*-benzenesulfonylaspartic acid, or *N*-benzoylglutamic acid.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] 1,2-Diaminopropane is used in the synthesis of *N*,*N′*-disalicylidene-1,2-propanediamine, a salen-type ligand, usually abbreviated as salpn, that is used as a metal deactivating additive in motor oils.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] 1,2-Diaminopropane forms coordination complexes similar to tris(ethylenediamine)cobalt(III).
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] Owing to the presence of the methyl groups, [Co(pn)3]3+ can exist as 24 stereoisomers.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] Two chiral 1,2-diamines are 1,2-diaminocyclohexane and 2,3-diaminobutane.
[src:antioxidant/1-2-diaminopropane] The chiral diastereomers of those diamines are C2-symmetric.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] It can be synthesised in a 2-step manner.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] Firstly, 2,4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is reacted with formaldehyde and HCl (Blanc reaction) to generate a chloromethyl group in the less hindered meta position.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] This intermediate then reacts with cyanuric acid to give the desired product.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] As each phenol group contains only a single t-butyl group they are considered to have low steric hindrance and thus high activity.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] Arranging three of these around an isocyanurate core gives a compound with a sufficiently high boiling point that it is not volatilised out of the plastic during plastic extrusion and moulding (up to 320 °C in the case of PA).
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] The isocyanurate core also promotes a high level of crystallinity, which greatly reduces extraction of the antioxidant into water.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] Although it is compatible with polyolefins Antioxidant 1790 is a fairly expensive antioxidant and it is primarily used in speciality applications.
[src:antioxidant/1-3-5-tris-4-tert-butyl-3-hydroxy-2-6-dimethylbenzyl-1-3-5-triazinane-2-4-6-trio] It has good compatibility with the engineering plastics, high activity and low colour formation, which makes it common choice in synthetic fibres (polyurethane, polyester and polyamide), particularly elastane.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used as an antioxidant, e.g. to prevent gumming in fuels, and as an ultraviolet stabilizer.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used in jet fuels, gasolines, and avgas.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is prepared by alkylation of xylenol with isobutylene.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] This alkylation provides a means to separate 2,4-xylenol from 2,5-xylenol since 2,4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is insoluble in 10% NaOH but 2,5-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is soluble.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] Subsequent to separation, the tert-butyl group can be removed in strong acid.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] One of its trade names is **Topanol A**.
[src:antioxidant/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is found in antioxidant mixtures AO-30, AO-31, AO-32, IONOL K72, IONOL K78, IONOL K98, and others.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Yet, according to the Environmental Working Group that does independent analyses and compiles peer-reviewed research, BHT is shown in multiple studies to cause damage to cells through production of metabolites and oxidative stress (Xu et al., 2021).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] These are mechanisms associated with a number of diseases including cancer.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is not a listed carcinogen, but some data have shown that it does cause cancer in animals.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] In high dose studies in animals it has been linked to hepatic toxicity, and the promotion of tumors in the liver, bladder, and lungs (Liu & Mabury, 2020; Xu et al., 2021).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT has been shown to cause developmental effects and thyroid changes in animals, suggesting that it may be able to disrupt endocrine signaling (European Food Safety Authority,2012).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] In certain high exposure scenarios, EFSA noted that children's dietary intake of BHT could exceed its acceptable daily intake, or ADI.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Phytoplankton, including the green algae *Botryococcus braunii*, as well as three different cyanobacteria (*Cylindrospermopsis raciborskii*, *Microcystis aeruginosa* and *Oscillatoria* sp.) are capable of producing BHT as a natural product.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The fruit lychee also produces BHT in its pericarp.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Several fungi (for example *Aspergillus conicus*) living in olives produce BHT.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Volatile organic compounds such as BHT and cresol are produced by resident fungi when olives are being stored awaiting pressing.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] It has been detected in higher plants and herbivorous insects, but it is not clear whether the BHT is produced by the plant, the insect, or some other organism living in association.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Alternatively, BHT has been prepared from 2,6-di-*tert*-butylphenol by hydroxymethylation or aminomethylation followed by hydrogenolysis.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The species behaves as a synthetic analog of vitamin E, primarily acting as a terminating agent that suppresses autoxidation, a process whereby unsaturated (usually) organic compounds are attacked by atmospheric oxygen.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT stops this autocatalytic reaction by converting peroxy radicals to hydroperoxides.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] where R is alkyl or aryl, and where ArOH is BHT or related phenolic antioxidants.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Meanwhile, the phenoxy radical generated by BHT is stabilized due to the delocalization of unpaired electrons around the aromatic ring and the steric hindrance effect of ortho *tert*-butyl groups.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is primarily used as an antioxidant food additive.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] In the United States, it is classified as generally recognized as safe (GRAS) based on a National Cancer Institute study from 1979 in rats and mice.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Recent research, however indicates reasons for health concerns (see Health effects section below for more details).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Recently, as EWG states: "BHT was shown in multiple studies to cause damage to cells through production of metabolites and oxidative stress (Xu et al., 2021).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Also, BHT is commonly consumed with other compounds in ultra-processed food (UPF), raising children's food additive levels.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] It is approved for use in the U.S. by the Food and Drug Administration: For example, 21 CFR § 137.350(a)(4) allows BHT up to 0.0033% by weight in "enriched rice", while 9 CFR § 381.147](f)(1) allows up to 0.01% in poultry "by fat content".
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] It is permitted in the European Union under E321.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] A reassessment of BHT safety was planned by the FDA for February, 2026.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is used as a preservative ingredient in some foods.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] With this usage BHT maintains freshness or prevents spoilage; it may be used to decrease the rate at which the texture, color, or flavor of food changes.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Some food companies have voluntarily eliminated BHT from their products or have announced that they were going to phase it out.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is also used as an antioxidant in products such as metalworking fluids, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals, rubber, transformer oils, and embalming fluid.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] In the petroleum industry, where BHT is known as the fuel additive AO-29 (Innospec), it is used in hydraulic fluids, turbine and gear oils, and jet fuels.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is also used to prevent peroxide formation in organic ethers and other solvents and laboratory chemicals.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] It is added to certain monomers as a polymerisation inhibitor to facilitate their safe storage.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Some additive products contain BHT as their primary ingredient, while others contain the chemical merely as a component of their formulation, sometimes alongside butylated hydroxyanisole (BHA).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT is also added as an antioxidant in consumer products such as polyurethane, which is used in mattresses, plastics, carpets and printing inks.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] From these products, it can migrate into the air and settle in house dust.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Although food is the most significant source of BHT exposure, dust has been reported to be an important source indoors (Liu & Mabury 2020), especially in children, who ingest more dust, on average (Wang et al 2015).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The European Union restricts the use of BHT in mouthwash to 0.001% concentration, in toothpaste to 0.01% concentration, and to 0.8% in other cosmetics.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Like many closely related phenolic antioxidants, BHT has low acute toxicity (e.g., the desmethyl analog of BHT, 2,6-di-tert-butylphenol, has an LD50 of >9 g/kg).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The US Food and Drug Administration classifies BHT as generally recognized as safe (GRAS) food preservative when used in an approved manner.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] In 1979, the National Cancer Institute determined that BHT was noncarcinogenic in a mouse model.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Yet recent research suggests reason for concern (see below).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The World Health Organization discussed a possible link between BHT and cancer risk in a 1986 report concluding there is limited evidence for carcinogenicity from animal studies.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Primary research studies in the 1970s–1990s reported both potential for increased risk and potential for decreased risk in the area of oncology.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Even at that time, increased cancer risk was therefore acknowledged.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] A review report published in 2002 noted that BHT has shown anticarcinogenic effects, no effect, or tumor promoting effects depending on animal species and target organ considered.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Because of this uncertainty, the Center for Science in the Public Interest puts BHT in its "caution" column and recommends avoiding it.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] from EWG: "The breakdown of BHT in the body into metabolites produces reactive intermediates that may pose risks to human health.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] While the cytotoxicity of BHT has long been recognized, recent studies published after its major regulatory evaluations have further clarified the precise mechanisms behind this cellular damage.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] The tumor-promoting effects of BHT are mainly influenced by production of quinone methylation metabolites such as BHT-QM (Xu et al., 2021).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Its metabolites are electrophilic, which means they bind well to cellular proteins and DNA (Lanigan and Yamarik, 2002).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Like BHA, its metabolite production causes oxidative stress, DNA damage and cell death (Castro et al., 2017).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] While BHT is not considered a carcinogen by IARC, its mechanisms are related to carcinogenesis.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] High-dose animal studies have linked BHT exposure to hepatic toxicity, endocrine disruption and the promotion of tumors in the liver, bladder, and lungs (Liu & Mabury 2020; Xu et al., 2021).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Oral studies in rats showed renal and hepatic damage at acute doses of 0.5 to 1.0 g/kg (Lanigan and Yamarik 2002).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] Subacute exposure at lower doses was linked to liver toxicity in rats (Moon et al., 1987).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol] BHT has been found in human cord blood (Du et al., 2019), breast milk (Zhang et al., 2020), serum (Liu & Mabury 2018), urine (Liu & Mabury 2018) and adipose tissue (Collings & Sharratt, 1970).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] In this way, approximately 2.5M kg/y are produced.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Alkylation of phenol usually favours the para-position, and a strong lewis acid such as the Al3+ ion is necessary to give selective ortho‑alkylation.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] If a conventional brønsted acid is used then 2,4-di-tert-butylphenol will be produced instead.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Two species of plants, *Jastropa curcas* and *Metaplexis japonica*, contain 2,6-DTBP in seeds.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-tert-butylphenol is used in the synthesis of 4,4′-biphenol.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] The process involves oxidative coupling of followed by removal of the tert-butyl groups.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-di-*tert*-butylphenol is a precursor to antioxidants and light-protection agents for the stabilization for polymers.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] One such case is methyl-3-(3,5-di-*tert*-butyl-4-hydroxyphenyl)-propionate (CAS# 6386-38-5), which is formed by the Michael addition of methyl acrylate.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] This compound is used in the synthesis of more complex antioxidants such as Irganox 1098.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-*tert*-butylphenol is also used in the synthesis of CGP-7930, probucol, and nicanartine.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] The LD50 is 9200 mg/kg, indicating a low toxicity.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-tert-butylphenol is covered by the U.S.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Department of Transportation Code of Federal Regulations 49 CFR 172.101, Appendix B (20 Dec 2004).
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] This substance is designated by the U.S.
[src:antioxidant/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Department of Transportation (DOT) as a marine pollutant.
[src:antioxidant/6-hydroxymelatonin] The determination of 6-OHM in human urine has been used to track the metabolism and excretion of melatonin using LC-MS/MS, providing quantifiable insights into circadian rhythm regulation and its oxidative role as a biomarker.
[src:antioxidant/6-hydroxymelatonin] 6-OHM is one of four of the primary metabolic products of melatonin in the liver and is also a byproduct of its breakdown due to exposure to light.
[src:antioxidant/6-hydroxymelatonin] It is known to be very effective in protecting cells from oxidative damage caused by ultraviolet (UV) radiation.
[src:antioxidant/6-hydroxymelatonin] Based on comparisons with other melatonin-related compounds, it is suggested that the protective effects of 6-OHM in mitigating oxidative stress are primarily attributed to their ability to scavenge free radicals.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Dietary antioxidants are vitamins A, C, and E, but the term has also been applied to various compounds that exhibit antioxidant properties in vitro, having little evidence for antioxidant properties in vivo.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Dietary supplements marketed as antioxidants have not been shown to maintain health or prevent disease in humans.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] As part of their adaptation from marine life, terrestrial plants began producing non-marine antioxidants such as ascorbic acid (vitamin C), polyphenols, and tocopherols.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The evolution of angiosperm plants between 50 and 200 million years ago resulted in the development of many antioxidant pigments – particularly during the Jurassic period – as chemical defences against reactive oxygen species that are byproducts of photosynthesis.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Originally, the term antioxidant specifically referred to a chemical that prevented the consumption of oxygen.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, extensive study concentrated on the use of antioxidants in important industrial processes, such as the prevention of metal corrosion, the vulcanization of rubber, and the polymerization of fuels in the fouling of internal combustion engines.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Early research on the role of antioxidants in biology focused on their use in preventing the oxidation of unsaturated fats, which is the cause of rancidity.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidant activity could be measured simply by placing the fat in a closed container with oxygen and measuring the rate of oxygen consumption.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] However, it was the identification of vitamins C and E as antioxidants that revolutionized the field and led to the realization of the importance of antioxidants in the biochemistry of living organisms.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The possible mechanisms of action of antioxidants were first explored when it was recognized that a substance with anti-oxidative activity is likely to be one that is itself readily oxidized.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Research into how vitamin E prevents the process of lipid peroxidation led to the identification of antioxidants as reducing agents that prevent oxidative reactions, often by scavenging reactive oxygen species before they can damage cells.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidants are added to food to prevent deterioration.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Exposure to oxygen and sunlight are the two main factors in the oxidation of food, so food is preserved by keeping in the dark and sealing it in containers or even coating it in wax, as with cucumbers.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] However, as oxygen is also important for plant respiration, storing plant materials in anaerobic conditions produces unpleasant flavors and unappealing colors.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Consequently, packaging of fresh fruits and vegetables contains an ≈8% oxygen atmosphere.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidants are an especially important class of preservatives as, unlike bacterial or fungal spoilage, oxidation reactions still occur relatively rapidly in frozen or refrigerated food.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These preservatives include natural antioxidants such as ascorbic acid (AA, E300) and tocopherols (E306), as well as synthetic antioxidants such as propyl gallate (PG, E310), tertiary butylhydroquinone (TBHQ), butylated hydroxyanisole (BHA, E320) and butylated hydroxytoluene (BHT, E321).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Unsaturated fats can be highly susceptible to oxidation, causing rancidification.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Oxidized lipids are often discolored and can impart unpleasant tastes and flavors.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Thus, these foods are rarely preserved by drying; instead, they are preserved by smoking, salting, or fermenting.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Even less fatty foods such as fruits are sprayed with sulfurous antioxidants prior to air drying.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Some fatty foods such as olive oil are partially protected from oxidation by their natural content of antioxidants.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Fatty foods are sensitive to photooxidation, which forms hydroperoxides by oxidizing unsaturated fatty acids and ester.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation can cause direct photooxidation and decompose peroxides and carbonyl molecules.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These molecules undergo free radical chain reactions, but antioxidants inhibit them by preventing the oxidation processes.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Some pharmaceutical products require protection from oxidation.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] A number of antioxidants can be used as excipients.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Sequestrants such as disodium EDTA can also be used to prevent metal-catalyzed oxidation.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidant stabilizers are also added to fat-based cosmetics such as lipstick and moisturizers to prevent rancidity.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidants in cosmetic products prevent oxidation of active ingredients and lipid content.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] For example, phenolic antioxidants such as stilbenes, flavonoids, and hydroxycinnamic acid strongly absorb UV radiation due to the presence of chromophores.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] They reduce oxidative stress from sun exposure by absorbing UV light.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidants may be added to industrial products, such as stabilizers in fuels and additives in lubricants, to prevent oxidation and polymerization that leads to the formation of engine-fouling residues.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidant polymer stabilizers are widely used to prevent the degradation of polymers, such as rubbers, plastics and adhesives, that causes a loss of strength and flexibility in these materials.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Polymers containing double bonds in their main chains, such as natural rubber and polybutadiene, are especially susceptible to oxidation and ozonolysis.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Oxidation can be accelerated by UV radiation in natural sunlight to cause photo-oxidation.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Various specialised light stabilisers, such as HALS may be added to plastics to prevent this.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Probucol was originally designed as an antioxidant polymer stabilizer for rubber tires.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] It was later found to reduce LDL-C levels independently of the LDL receptor and became a prescription drug.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Its approval predated statins by a decade.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Synthetic phenolic antioxidants (SPAs) and aminic antioxidants have potential human and environmental health hazards.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] SPAs are common in indoor dust, small air particles, sediment, sewage, river water and wastewater.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] They are synthesized from phenolic compounds and include 2,6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol (BHT), 2,6-di-tert-butyl-p-benzoquinone (BHT-Q), 2,4-di-tert-butyl-phenol (DBP) and 3-*tert*-butyl-4-hydroxyanisole (BHA).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] BHT can cause hepatotoxicity and damage to the endocrine system and may increase the carcinogenicity of 1,1-dimethylhydrazine exposure.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] BHT-Q can cause DNA damage and mismatches through the cleavage process, generating superoxide radicals.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] DBP is toxic to marine life if exposed long-term.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Phenolic antioxidants have low biodegradability, but they do not have severe toxicity toward aquatic organisms at low concentrations.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Another type of antioxidant, diphenylamine (DPA), is commonly used in the production of commercial, industrial lubricants and rubber products and it also acts as a supplement for automotive engine oils.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The vast majority of complex life on Earth requires oxygen for its metabolism, but this same oxygen is a highly reactive element that can damage living organisms.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Organisms contain chemicals and enzymes that minimize this oxidative damage without interfering with the beneficial effect of oxygen.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In general, antioxidant systems either prevent these reactive species from being formed, or remove them, thus minimizing their damage.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Reactive oxygen species can have useful cellular functions, such as redox signaling.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Thus, ideally, antioxidant systems do not remove oxidants entirely, but maintain them at some optimum concentration.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Reactive oxygen species produced in cells include hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), hypochlorous acid (HClO), and free radicals such as the hydroxyl radical (·OH), and the superoxide anion (O2−).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The hydroxyl radical is particularly unstable and will react rapidly and non-specifically with most biological molecules.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This species is produced from hydrogen peroxide in metal-catalyzed redox reactions such as the Fenton reaction.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These oxidants can damage cells by starting chemical chain reactions such as lipid peroxidation, or by oxidizing DNA or proteins.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Damage to DNA can cause mutations and possibly cancer, if not reversed by DNA repair mechanisms, while damage to proteins causes enzyme inhibition, denaturation, and protein degradation.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The use of oxygen as part of the process for generating metabolic energy produces reactive oxygen species.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In this process, the superoxide anion is produced as a by-product of several steps in the electron transport chain.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Particularly important is the reduction of coenzyme Q in complex III, since a highly reactive free radical is formed as an intermediate (Q**·**−).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This unstable intermediate can lead to electron "leakage", when electrons jump directly to oxygen and form the superoxide anion, instead of moving through the normal series of well-controlled reactions of the electron transport chain.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Peroxide is also produced from the oxidation of reduced flavoproteins, such as complex I.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] However, although these enzymes can produce oxidants, the relative importance of the electron transfer chain to other processes that generate peroxide is unclear.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In plants, algae, and cyanobacteria, reactive oxygen species are also produced during photosynthesis, particularly under conditions of high light intensity.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Physiological antioxidants are classified into two broad divisions, depending on whether they are soluble in water (hydrophilic) or in lipids (lipophilic).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In general, water-soluble antioxidants react with oxidants in the cell cytosol and the blood plasma, while lipid-soluble antioxidants protect cell membranes from lipid peroxidation.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These compounds may be synthesized in the body or obtained from the diet.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The different antioxidants are present at a wide range of concentrations in body fluids and tissues, with some such as glutathione or ubiquinone mostly present within cells, while others such as uric acid are more systemically distributed (see table below).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Some antioxidants are only found in a few organisms, and can be pathogens or virulence factors.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The interactions between these different antioxidants may be synergistic and interdependent.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The action of one antioxidant may therefore depend on the proper function of other members of the antioxidant system.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The amount of protection provided by any one antioxidant will also depend on its concentration, its reactivity towards the particular reactive oxygen species being considered, and the status of the antioxidants with which it interacts.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Some compounds contribute to antioxidant defense by chelating transition metals and preventing them from catalyzing the production of free radicals in the cell.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The ability to sequester iron for iron-binding proteins, such as transferrin and ferritin, is one such function.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Selenium and zinc are commonly referred to as *antioxidant minerals*, but these chemical elements have no antioxidant action themselves, but rather are required for the activity of antioxidant enzymes, such as glutathione reductase and superoxide dismutase.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Uric acid has the highest concentration of any blood antioxidant and provides over half of the total antioxidant capacity of human serum.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Uric acid's antioxidant activities are also complex, given that it does not react with some oxidants, such as superoxide, but does act against peroxynitrite, peroxides, and hypochlorous acid.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Concerns over elevated UA's contribution to gout must be considered one of many risk factors.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] By itself, UA-related risk of gout at high levels (415–530 μmol/L) is only 0.5% per year with an increase to 4.5% per year at UA supersaturation levels (535+ μmol/L).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Many of these aforementioned studies determined UA's antioxidant actions within normal physiological levels, and some found antioxidant activity at levels as high as 285 μmol/L.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Ascorbic acid or vitamin C, an oxidation-reduction (redox) catalyst found in both animals and plants, can reduce, and thereby neutralize, reactive oxygen species, such as hydrogen peroxide.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In addition to its direct antioxidant effects, ascorbic acid is also a substrate for the redox enzyme ascorbate peroxidase, a function that is used in stress resistance in plants.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Ascorbic acid is present at high levels in all parts of plants and can reach concentrations of 20 millimolar in chloroplasts.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Glutathione has antioxidant properties since the thiol group in its cysteine moiety is a reducing agent and can be reversibly oxidized and reduced.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In cells, glutathione is maintained in the reduced form by the enzyme glutathione reductase and in turn reduces other metabolites and enzyme systems, such as ascorbate in the glutathione-ascorbate cycle, glutathione peroxidases and glutaredoxins, as well as reacting directly with oxidants.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Due to its high concentration and its central role in maintaining the cell's redox state, glutathione is one of the most important cellular antioxidants.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In some organisms glutathione is replaced by other thiols, such as by mycothiol in the Actinomycetes, bacillithiol in some gram-positive bacteria, or by trypanothione in the Kinetoplastids.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] A derivative of glutathione, glutathione hydropersulfide, operates as an abundant radical-trapping antioxidant with greater potency against free radical oxidation than glutathione itself.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Vitamin E is the collective name for a set of eight related tocopherols and tocotrienols, which are fat-soluble vitamins with antioxidant properties.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Of these, α-tocopherol has been most studied as it has the highest bioavailability, with the body preferentially absorbing and metabolising this form.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Alpha-tocopherol is the lipid-soluble antioxidant that protects membranes from oxidation by reacting with lipid radicals produced in the lipid peroxidation chain reaction.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This removes the free radical intermediates and prevents the propagation reaction from continuing.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This reaction produces oxidized α-tocopheroxyl radicals that can be recycled back to the active reduced form by other antioxidants, such as ascorbate.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The functions of the other forms of vitamin E are less well understood, although γ-tocopherol is a nucleophile that may react with electrophilic mutagens, and tocotrienols may be important in protecting neurons from damage.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidants that are reducing agents can also act as pro-oxidants.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] For example, vitamin C has antioxidant activity when it reduces oxidizing substances such as hydrogen peroxide; however, it will also reduce metal ions such as iron and copper that generate free radicals through the Fenton reaction.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] While ascorbic acid is effective antioxidant, it can also oxidatively change the flavor and color of food.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] With the presence of transition metals, there are low concentrations of ascorbic acid that can act as a radical scavenger in the Fenton reaction.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The relative importance of the antioxidant and pro-oxidant activities of antioxidants is an area of current research, but vitamin C, which exerts its effects as a vitamin by oxidizing polypeptides, appears to have a mostly antioxidant action in the human body.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] As with the chemical antioxidants, cells are protected against oxidative stress by an interacting network of antioxidant enzymes.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Here, the superoxide released by processes such as oxidative phosphorylation is first converted to hydrogen peroxide and then further reduced to give water.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This detoxification pathway is the result of multiple enzymes, with superoxide dismutases catalysing the first step and then catalases and various peroxidases removing hydrogen peroxide.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] As with antioxidant metabolites, the contributions of these enzymes to antioxidant defenses can be hard to separate from one another, but the generation of transgenic mice lacking just one antioxidant enzyme can be informative.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Superoxide dismutases (SODs) are a class of closely related enzymes that catalyze the breakdown of the superoxide anion into oxygen and hydrogen peroxide.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] SOD enzymes are present in almost all aerobic cells and in extracellular fluids.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Superoxide dismutase enzymes contain metal ion cofactors that, depending on the isozyme, can be copper, zinc, manganese or iron.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In humans, the copper/zinc SOD is present in the cytosol, while manganese SOD is present in the mitochondrion.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] There also exists a third form of SOD in extracellular fluids, which contains copper and zinc in its active sites.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The mitochondrial isozyme seems to be the most biologically important of these three, since mice lacking this enzyme die soon after birth.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In contrast, the mice lacking copper/zinc SOD (Sod1) are viable but have numerous pathologies and a reduced lifespan (see article on superoxide), while mice without the extracellular SOD have minimal defects (sensitive to hyperoxia).
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In plants, SOD isozymes are present in the cytosol and mitochondria, with an iron SOD found in chloroplasts that is absent from vertebrates and yeast.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Catalases are enzymes that catalyse the conversion of hydrogen peroxide to water and oxygen, using either an iron or manganese cofactor.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This protein is localized to peroxisomes in most eukaryotic cells.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Catalase is an unusual enzyme since, although hydrogen peroxide is its only substrate, it follows a ping-pong mechanism.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Here, its cofactor is oxidised by one molecule of hydrogen peroxide and then regenerated by transferring the bound oxygen to a second molecule of substrate.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Despite its apparent importance in hydrogen peroxide removal, humans with genetic deficiency of catalase — "acatalasemia" — or mice genetically engineered to lack catalase completely, experience few ill effects.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Peroxiredoxins are peroxidases that catalyze the reduction of hydrogen peroxide, organic hydroperoxides, as well as peroxynitrite.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] They are divided into three classes: typical 2-cysteine peroxiredoxins; atypical 2-cysteine peroxiredoxins; and 1-cysteine peroxiredoxins.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These enzymes share the same basic catalytic mechanism, in which a redox-active cysteine (the peroxidatic cysteine) in the active site is oxidized to a sulfenic acid by the peroxide substrate.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Over-oxidation of this cysteine residue in peroxiredoxins inactivates these enzymes, but this can be reversed by the action of sulfiredoxin.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Peroxiredoxins seem to be important in antioxidant metabolism, as mice lacking peroxiredoxin 1 or 2 have shortened lifespans and develop hemolytic anaemia, while plants use peroxiredoxins to remove hydrogen peroxide generated in chloroplasts.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The thioredoxin system contains the 12 kDa protein thioredoxin and its companion thioredoxin reductase.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Proteins related to thioredoxin are present in all sequenced organisms.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Plants, such as *Arabidopsis thaliana,* have a particularly great diversity of isoforms.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The active site of thioredoxin consists of two neighboring cysteines, as part of a highly conserved CXXC motif, that can cycle between an active dithiol form (reduced) and an oxidized disulfide form.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In its active state, thioredoxin acts as an efficient reducing agent, scavenging reactive oxygen species and maintaining other proteins in their reduced state.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] After being oxidized, the active thioredoxin is regenerated by the action of thioredoxin reductase, using NADPH as an electron donor.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The glutathione system includes glutathione, glutathione reductase, glutathione peroxidases, and glutathione *S*-transferases.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This system is found in animals, plants and microorganisms.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Glutathione peroxidase is an enzyme containing four selenium-cofactors that catalyzes the breakdown of hydrogen peroxide and organic hydroperoxides.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] There are at least four different glutathione peroxidase isozymes in animals.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Glutathione peroxidase 1 is the most abundant and is a very efficient scavenger of hydrogen peroxide, while glutathione peroxidase 4 is most active with lipid hydroperoxides.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Surprisingly, glutathione peroxidase 1 is dispensable, as mice lacking this enzyme have normal lifespans, but they are hypersensitive to induced oxidative stress.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In addition, the glutathione *S*-transferases show high activity with lipid peroxides.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These enzymes are at particularly high levels in the liver and also serve in detoxification metabolism.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The dietary antioxidant vitamins A, C, and E are essential and required in specific daily amounts to prevent diseases.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Polyphenols, which have antioxidant properties in vitro due to their free hydroxy groups, are extensively metabolized by catechol-O-methyltransferase which methylates free hydroxyl groups, and thereby prevents them from acting as antioxidants in vivo.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Common pharmaceuticals (and supplements) with antioxidant properties may interfere with the efficacy of certain anticancer medications and radiation therapy.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Pharmaceuticals and supplements that have antioxidant properties suppress the formation of free radicals by inhibiting oxidation processes.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Radiation therapy induces oxidative stress that damages essential components of cancer cells, such as proteins, nucleic acids, and lipids that comprise cell membranes.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Relatively strong reducing acids can have antinutrient effects by binding to dietary minerals such as iron and zinc in the gastrointestinal tract and preventing them from being absorbed.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Examples are oxalic acid, tannins and phytic acid, which are high in plant-based diets.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Calcium and iron deficiencies are not uncommon in diets in developing countries where less meat is eaten and there is high consumption of phytic acid from beans and unleavened whole grain bread.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] However, germination, soaking, or microbial fermentation are all household strategies that reduce the phytate and polyphenol content of unrefined cereal.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Increases in Fe, Zn and Ca absorption have been reported in adults fed dephytinized cereals compared with cereals containing their native phytate.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] High doses of some antioxidants may have harmful long-term effects.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The *Beta-Carotene and Retinol Efficacy Trial* (CARET) study of lung cancer patients found that smokers given supplements containing beta-carotene and vitamin A had increased rates of lung cancer.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These harmful effects may also be seen in non-smokers, as one meta-analysis including data from approximately 230,000 patients showed that β-carotene, vitamin A or vitamin E supplementation is associated with increased mortality, but saw no significant effect from vitamin C.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] No health risk was seen when all the randomized controlled studies were examined together, but an increase in mortality was detected when only high-quality and low-bias risk trials were examined separately.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] As the majority of these low-bias trials dealt with either elderly people, smokers, or people with disease, these results may not apply to the general population.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] This meta-analysis was later repeated and extended by the same authors, confirming the previous results.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] These two publications are consistent with some previous meta-analyses that also suggested that vitamin E supplementation increased mortality, and that antioxidant supplements increased the risk of colon cancer.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In the Selenium and Vitamin E Cancer Prevention Trial (SELECT study), vitamin E – alone or combined with selenium – had no effect on the risk of prostate cancer.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Beta-carotene may also increase lung cancer.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Overall, the large number of clinical trials carried out on antioxidant supplements suggest that either these products have no effect on health, or that they cause a small increase in mortality in elderly or vulnerable populations.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] A 2017 review showed that taking antioxidant dietary supplements before or after exercise is unlikely to produce a noticeable reduction in muscle soreness after a person exercises.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Antioxidant vitamins are found in vegetables, fruits, eggs, legumes and nuts.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Vitamins A, C, and E can be destroyed by long-term storage or prolonged cooking.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] The effects of cooking and food processing are complex, as these processes can also increase the bioavailability of antioxidants, such as some carotenoids in vegetables.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Processed food contains fewer antioxidant vitamins than fresh and uncooked foods, as preparation exposes food to heat and oxygen.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Other antioxidants are not obtained from the diet, but instead are made in the body.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] For example, ubiquinol (coenzyme Q) is poorly absorbed from the gut and is made through the mevalonate pathway.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Another example is glutathione, which is made from amino acids.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] As any glutathione in the gut is broken down to free cysteine, glycine and glutamic acid before being absorbed, even large oral intake has little effect on the concentration of glutathione in the body.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Although large amounts of sulfur-containing amino acids such as acetylcysteine can increase glutathione, no evidence exists that eating high levels of these glutathione precursors is beneficial for healthy adults.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Measurement of polyphenol and carotenoid content in food is not a straightforward process, as antioxidants collectively are a diverse group of compounds with different reactivities to various reactive oxygen species.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] In food science analyses in vitro, the oxygen radical absorbance capacity (ORAC) was once an industry standard for estimating antioxidant strength of whole foods, juices and food additives, mainly from the presence of polyphenols.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Earlier measurements and ratings by the United States Department of Agriculture were withdrawn in 2012 as biologically irrelevant to human health, referring to an absence of physiological evidence for polyphenols having antioxidant properties *in vivo*.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Consequently, the ORAC method, derived only from *in vitro* experiments, is no longer considered relevant to human diets or biology, as of 2010.
[src:antioxidant/antioxidant] Alternative in vitro measurements of antioxidant content in foods – also based on the presence of polyphenols – include the Folin-Ciocalteu reagent, and the Trolox equivalent antioxidant capacity assay.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Stilbene was discovered in 1843 by the French chemist Auguste Laurent.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The name "stilbene" is derived from the Greek word *στίλβω* (*stilbo*), which means "I shine", on account of the lustrous appearance of the compound.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Stilbene exists as two possible stereoisomers.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] One is *trans*-1,2-diphenylethylene, called (*E*)-stilbene or *trans*-stilbene.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The second is *cis*-1,2-diphenylethylene, called (*Z*)-stilbene or *cis*-stilbene, and is sterically hindered and less stable because the steric interactions force the aromatic rings out-of-plane and prevent conjugation.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] *Cis*-stilbene is a liquid at room temperature (melting point: 5–6 °C (41–43 °F)), while *trans*-stilbene is a crystalline solid which does not melt until around 125 °C (257 °F), illustrating the two isomers have significantly different physical properties.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] One popular route entails reduction of benzoin using zinc amalgam.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Both isomers of stilbene can be produced by decarboxylation of α-phenylcinnamic acid, *trans*-stilbene being produced from the (*Z*)-isomer of the acid.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Heck and Tsutomu Mizoroki independently reported the synthesis of *trans*-stilbene by coupling of iodobenzene and styrene using a palladium(II) catalyst, in what is now known as the Mizoroki-Heck reaction.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The Mizoroki approach produced the higher yield.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Stilbene undergoes reactions typical of alkenes.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] *Trans*-stilbene undergoes epoxidation with peroxymonophosphoric acid, H3PO5, producing a 74% yield of *trans*-stilbene oxide in dioxane.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The epoxide product formed is a racemic mixture of the two enantiomers of 1,2-diphenyloxirane.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The achiral *meso* compound (1*R*,2*S*)-1,2-diphenyloxirane arises from *cis*-stilbene, though peroxide epoxidations of the *cis*-isomer produce both *cis*- and *trans*-epoxide products.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] For example, using *tert*-butyl hydroperoxide, oxidation of *cis*-stilbene produces 0.8% *cis*-stilbene oxide, 13.5% *trans*-stilbene oxide, and 6.1% benzaldehyde.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Enantiopure stilbene oxide has been prepared by Nobel laureate Karl Barry Sharpless.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Stilbene can be cleanly oxidised to benzaldehyde by ozonolysis or Lemieux–Johnson oxidation, and stronger oxidants such as acidified potassium permanganate will produce benzoic acid.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Vicinal diols can be produced via the Upjohn dihydroxylation or enantioselectively using Sharpless asymmetric dihydroxylation with enantiomeric excesses as high as 100%.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The addition of bromide or tribromide salts restores much of the stereospecificity even in solvents with a dielectric constant above 35.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Upon UV irradiation it converts to *cis*-stilbene, a classic example of a photochemical reaction involving *trans*-*cis* isomerization, and can undergo further reaction to form phenanthrene.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] (*E*)-Stilbene itself is of little value, but it is a precursor to other derivatives used as dyes, optical brighteners, phosphors, and scintillators.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Stilbene is one of the gain mediums used in dye lasers.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Improvements to the process with higher yields have been developed, using air oxidation in liquid ammonia.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The product is useful as its reaction with aniline derivatives results in the formation of azo dyes.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Commercially important dyes derived from this compound include Direct Red 76, Direct Brown 78, and Direct Orange 40.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The stilbenoids are naturally occurring stilbene derivatives.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Examples include resveratrol and its cousin, pterostilbene.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] The stilbestrols, which are structurally but not synthetically related to (*E*)-stilbene, exhibit estrogenic activity.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Members of this group include diethylstilbestrol, fosfestrol, and dienestrol.
[src:antioxidant/e-stilbene] Some such derivative are produced by condensation of coenzyme A derivatives of cinnamic acid or 4-hydroxycinnamic acid and the malonic acid.
